      <div class="mission">
          <a href="#" class="btn btn-grey"><span>Mission</span></a>
          <p class="mt-3">
            <p style="text-align: center; ">“1776” is an assembly of independent voices who uphold our country’s authentic founding virtues and values and challenge those who assert America is forever defined by its past failures, such as slavery. We seek to offer alternative perspectives that celebrate the progress America has made on delivering its promise of equality and opportunity and highlight the resilience of its people. Our focus is on solving problems.</p><p style="text-align: center; ">We do this in the spirit of 1776, the date of America’s true founding.</p>
          </p>
          <div class="card card-video text-white">
            <div class="card-img">
              <iframe id="player" width="100%" height="657" src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/391328342?embedparameter=value" frameborder="0" allow="autoplay; encrypted-media" allowfullscreen></iframe>
            </div>
            <div class="card-img-overlay">
              <div class="credits">
                <p class="card-title"></p>
                <p class="card-author"></p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
      </div>
      <div class="section-separator"></div>
      <main class="main">
          <div class="main__part">
            <h2 class="section-title text-center mb-4">Featured</h2>
            <div class="row">
                <div class="col-sm-6 news-preview_col">
                  <div class="card news-preview">
                            <a href="http://1776unites.com/scholars" class="news-label red absolute"> 
        Essays
      </a>

                            <a href="http://1776unites.com/scholars/shelby-steele/essay/525692190"> 
          <img src="https://jnswire.s3.amazonaws.com/jns-media/91/81/11398268/shelby_steele.png" class="card-img-top" alt="An excerpt from "Shame"">
        </a> 

                    <div class="card-body p-0">
                      <h3 class="card-title">
                              <a href="http://1776unites.com/scholars/shelby-steele/essay/525692190"> 
        An excerpt from "Shame"
      </a>

                      </h3>
                      <p class="card-date">
                          <span>By </span>       <a href="http://1776unites.com/scholars/shelby_steele/bio/525692190">Shelby Steele</a>

                        &nbsp;|&nbsp;
                        <a href="/stories/2020/feb">Feb 17, 2020</a>
                      </p>
                      <p class="card-text">
                        When I traveled to Africa back in 1970, it was partly because I had been more and more seduced by this great looming idea of America’s characterological evil. It was such a summary judgment, and, at the time, still new and audacious. It had not existed in the original civil rights movement of ﻿the 1950s and early 1960s.
                      </p>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="col-sm-6 news-preview_col">
                  <div class="card news-preview">
                            <a href="http://1776unites.com/scholars" class="news-label red absolute"> 
        Essays
      </a>

                            <a href="http://1776unites.com/scholars/clarence-page/essay/525692123"> 
          <img src="https://jnswire.s3.amazonaws.com/jns-media/95/f4/11397878/page.png" class="card-img-top" alt="‘A dream as old as the American dream’: Embrace black patriotism over victimization">
        </a> 

                    <div class="card-body p-0">
                      <h3 class="card-title">
                              <a href="http://1776unites.com/scholars/clarence-page/essay/525692123"> 
        ‘A dream as old as the American dream’: Embrace black patriotism over victimization
      </a>

                      </h3>
                      <p class="card-date">
                          <span>By </span>       <a href="http://1776unites.com/scholars/clarence_page/bio/525692123">Clarence Page</a>

                        &nbsp;|&nbsp;
                        <a href="/stories/2020/feb">Feb 17, 2020</a>
                      </p>
                      <p class="card-text">
                        In 2019, marking 400 years since the first known Africans arrived on these shores from West Africa as slaves, the New York Times launched its ambitious 1619 Project. It aimed to reexamine U.S. history through the lens of black history — as if American history began with the arrival of the first black folks.
                      </p>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="col-sm-6 news-preview_col">
                  <div class="card news-preview">
                            <a href="http://1776unites.com/scholars" class="news-label red absolute"> 
        Essays
      </a>

                            <a href="http://1776unites.com/scholars/john-mcwhorter/essay/525505452"> 
          <img src="https://jnswire.s3.amazonaws.com/jns-media/58/c0/11395504/mcwhorter.png" class="card-img-top" alt="The 1619 Project Depicts an America Tainted by Original Sin">
        </a> 

                    <div class="card-body p-0">
                      <h3 class="card-title">
                              <a href="http://1776unites.com/scholars/john-mcwhorter/essay/525505452"> 
        The 1619 Project Depicts an America Tainted by Original Sin
      </a>

                      </h3>
                      <p class="card-date">
                          <span>By </span>       <a href="http://1776unites.com/scholars/john_mcwhorter/bio/525505452">John McWhorter</a>

                        &nbsp;|&nbsp;
                        <a href="/stories/2020/feb">Feb 14, 2020</a>
                      </p>
                      <p class="card-text">
                        Since last August, The New York Times has asked us to consider that America&#39;s real founding was not in 1776 but in 1619, when the first Africans were brought to these shores. Nikole Hannah-Jones teaches that the Revolutionary War was fought mainly not to escape British tyranny, but out of fear that British tyranny was about to threaten the institution of slavery.
                      </p>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="col-sm-6 news-preview_col">
                  <div class="card news-preview">
                            <a href="http://1776unites.com/scholars" class="news-label red absolute"> 
        Essays
      </a>

                            <a href="http://1776unites.com/scholars/jason-d-hill/essay/525116938"> 
          <img src="https://jnswire.s3.amazonaws.com/jns-media/dd/74/11397961/hill.png" class="card-img-top" alt="The Moral Meaning of America: Two Parallel Narratives">
        </a> 

                    <div class="card-body p-0">
                      <h3 class="card-title">
                              <a href="http://1776unites.com/scholars/jason-d-hill/essay/525116938"> 
        The Moral Meaning of America: Two Parallel Narratives
      </a>

                      </h3>
                      <p class="card-date">
                          <span>By </span>       <a href="http://1776unites.com/scholars/jason_d_hill/bio/525116938">Jason D. Hill</a>

                        &nbsp;|&nbsp;
                        <a href="/stories/2020/feb">Feb 13, 2020</a>
                      </p>
                      <p class="card-text">
                        Race has been endemic to American life from its inception. But I think race always was metaphysically irrelevant to the true spirit of America. Race, like the slavery that is America’s tragic birth defect, was a betrayal of the essential moral meaning of America.
                      </p>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="col-sm-6 news-preview_col">
                  <div class="card news-preview">
                            <a href="http://1776unites.com/scholars" class="news-label red absolute"> 
        Essays
      </a>

                            <a href="http://1776unites.com/scholars/wilfred-reilly/essay/525116911"> 
          <img src="https://jnswire.s3.amazonaws.com/jns-media/eb/37/11394497/reilly.png" class="card-img-top" alt="Slavery does not define the black American experience">
        </a> 

                    <div class="card-body p-0">
                      <h3 class="card-title">
                              <a href="http://1776unites.com/scholars/wilfred-reilly/essay/525116911"> 
        Slavery does not define the black American experience
      </a>

                      </h3>
                      <p class="card-date">
                          <span>By </span>       <a href="http://1776unites.com/scholars/wilfred_reilly/bio/525116911">Wilfred Reilly</a>

                        &nbsp;|&nbsp;
                        <a href="/stories/2020/feb">Feb 13, 2020</a>
                      </p>
                      <p class="card-text">
                        Slavery was horrible, but it was not the primary factor that built this country, and its historical existence does not permanently stain our nation’s legacy. It should never be denied — and no one in fact does deny this — that the “land of the free” once used captives from other societies almost as cattle.
                      </p>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="col-sm-6 news-preview_col">
                  <div class="card news-preview">
                            <a href="http://1776unites.com/scholars" class="news-label red absolute"> 
        Essays
      </a>

                            <a href="http://1776unites.com/scholars/john-wood-jr/essay/525075325"> 
          <img src="https://jnswire.s3.amazonaws.com/jns-media/d9/b9/11394487/johnwood.png" class="card-img-top" alt="Acknowledging Slavery’s Limits in Defining America">
        </a> 

                    <div class="card-body p-0">
                      <h3 class="card-title">
                              <a href="http://1776unites.com/scholars/john-wood-jr/essay/525075325"> 
        Acknowledging Slavery’s Limits in Defining America
      </a>

                      </h3>
                      <p class="card-date">
                          <span>By </span>       <a href="http://1776unites.com/scholars/john_wood_jr/bio/525075325">John Wood, Jr.</a>

                        &nbsp;|&nbsp;
                        <a href="/stories/2020/feb">Feb 13, 2020</a>
                      </p>
                      <p class="card-text">
                        To be black in America is to have some relationship to the historic tragedy of slavery. American slavery, often referred to as a type of chattel slavery, as unique as a condition of servitude in the tortured history of forced bondage in the human race. 
                      </p>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="col-sm-6 news-preview_col">
                  <div class="card news-preview">
                            <a href="http://1776unites.com/scholars" class="news-label red absolute"> 
        Essays
      </a>

                            <a href="http://1776unites.com/scholars/robert-l-woodson-sr/essay/525075303"> 
          <img src="https://jnswire.s3.amazonaws.com/jns-media/26/09/11394485/woodson.png" class="card-img-top" alt="The Crucial Voice of “1776"">
        </a> 

                    <div class="card-body p-0">
                      <h3 class="card-title">
                              <a href="http://1776unites.com/scholars/robert-l-woodson-sr/essay/525075303"> 
        The Crucial Voice of “1776"
      </a>

                      </h3>
                      <p class="card-date">
                          <span>By </span>       <a href="http://1776unites.com/scholars/robert_l_woodson_sr/bio/525075303">Robert L. Woodson, Sr.</a>

                        &nbsp;|&nbsp;
                        <a href="/stories/2020/feb">Feb 13, 2020</a>
                      </p>
                      <p class="card-text">
                        While the country’s chatting classes have had their attention riveted on the impeachment of the president and the national elections to take place this year, the moral ground under our feet has been shaking with small seismic tremors that portend a coming major eruption that could tear this country apart. As those who promote identity politics fan the flames of animosity and thrive on division, our nation is breaking apart.
                      </p>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="col-sm-6 news-preview_col">
                  <div class="card news-preview">
                            <a href="http://1776unites.com/scholars" class="news-label red absolute"> 
        Essays
      </a>

                            <a href="http://1776unites.com/scholars/stephanie-deutsch/essay/525169037"> 
          <img src="https://jnswire.s3.amazonaws.com/jns-media/de/0e/11394520/deutsch.png" class="card-img-top" alt="Closing the Black-White Educational Gap in the South in the Early 20th Century">
        </a> 

                    <div class="card-body p-0">
                      <h3 class="card-title">
                              <a href="http://1776unites.com/scholars/stephanie-deutsch/essay/525169037"> 
        Closing the Black-White Educational Gap in the South in the Early 20th Century
      </a>

                      </h3>
                      <p class="card-date">
                          <span>By </span>       <a href="http://1776unites.com/scholars/stephanie_deutsch/bio/525169037">Stephanie Deutsch</a>

                        &nbsp;|&nbsp;
                        <a href="/stories/2020/feb">Feb 10, 2020</a>
                      </p>
                      <p class="card-text">
                        Shortly after the publication of my book, “You Need a Schoolhouse: Booker T. Washington, Julius Rosenwald and the Building of Schools for the Segregated South,” an interviewer asked me, “What was your big takeaway from the research you did?” I had never asked myself quite that question, but it didn’t take me long to find the answer: Respect for African Americans.
                      </p>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
            </div>
          </div>
      </main>
